Found a bug with the order formats are specified.

Lets say `req.accepts()` returns `[ 'application/json', 'text/plain', '*/*' ]` and the code looks like this:

```
res.format({
    html: function () {
        // this is always called
        res.render('hello');
    },
    json: function () {
        res.send(200, { hello: "world" })
    }
})
```

The html function will be called, not the json one.

If you reverse the order (json then html in res.format (see bottom of the comment)), it calls the json function as it should.

```
console.log(req.accepts())
res.format({
    json: function () {
        // this is called if the requested content is json
        res.send(200, { hello: "world" })
    },
    html: function () {
        res.render('hello');
    }
})
```

It seems like a bug, because it causes unexpected behaviour, but looking at the req.accepts() it correctly calls the html.

I am willing to create a patch, if this is accepted as a bug :)

